1. Introduction

Geospatial risk modeling is used to predict the crime risk based on the exposure to risk factors. It needs to be noticed that selection bias may exist in both dependent variable and the risk features. This project breaks down the process of building an algorithm while highlighting the selection bias that exist in different stage. This model is using the 2020 and 2021 gun crime data from the city of Chicago data portal (https://data.cityofchicago.org/Public-Safety/Gun-Crimes-Heat-Map/iinq-m3rg) to predict future locations of gun shooting crimes.

Sweeney found that Chicago endured one of its deadliest years in at least the last quarter-century in 2021. There are over 17,000 cases of gun crimes in 2020 according to the dataset. In the creation process of this gun crime dataset, including gun crimes reporting, officer judgement, the bias could exist in different phases, influenced by sociopolitical, environmental, and behavioral factors. Additionally, the factors that are seen as variables for gun crime, like low income and racial factors, would assume that peoples characteristics lead them to commit crimes, which is another phase for bias to happen.

It is critical to build the risk model while being aware of the bias and the way we interpret the model in different phases.

This fact may decrease the reliability of the gun crime dataset, which this risk model would be based on.

3.2 Fishnet grid

To set up a geospatial framework for the further analysis, we create the fishnet grids of 500-meter cells withing Chicago city boundary. We are aggregating the point data into the fishnet grid to visualize the hot spot of gun crimes.

## using {sf} to create the grid
## Note the `.[chicagoBoundary] %>% ` line. This is needed to clip the grid to our data
fishnet <- 
  st_make_grid(chicagoBoundary,
               cellsize = 500, 
               square = TRUE) %>%
  .[chicagoBoundary] %>%            # fast way to select intersecting polygons
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = 1:n())
## add a value of 1 to each crime, sum them with aggregate
crime_net <- 
  dplyr::select(gunshoot) %>% 
  mutate(countgunshoot = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countgunshoot = replace_na(countgunshoot, 0),
         uniqueID = 1:n(),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 24), 
                       size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = crime_net, aes(fill = countgunshoot), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title = "Count of gun crimes for the fishnet") +
  mapTheme()

4. Risk variables and feature engineering

4.1 Risk factors selection

In the part, we are searching for the potential spatial risk variables that might lead to the occurrences of gun crimes. The risk factors selection is based on the Broken Windows Theory, which posits a link between disorder in community environment and crime.

We import the factors of abandoned cars, abandoned buildings, graffiti, broken street lights, sanitation, liquor retail, environmental complaint, tree trim request and tree debris report. Most of the factors are the performance of poor and disordered community environment and thus link to the bias.

## only pulling a single variable for our model to keep it simple

4.2 Feature engineering

Then, we use nearest neighbor function to do the feature engineering for the selected potential factors. By calculating the mean distance from each fishnet center point to its 3 nearest risk factor points, we get the variables: Abandoned_Buildings.nn, Graffiti.nn, Liquor_Retail.nn, Street_Lights_Out.nn, Sanitation.nn, Envir_Complaint.nn, Tree_Trim.nn, Tree_Debris.nn.

# convinience to reduce length of function names.
st_c    <- st_coordinates
st_coid <- st_centroid

## create NN from abandoned cars
vars_net <- vars_net %>%
    mutate(
      Abandoned_Cars.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(abandonCars),3),
       Abandoned_Buildings.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(abandonBuildings),3),
      Graffiti.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(graffiti),3),
      Liquor_Retail.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(liquorRetail),3),
      Street_Lights_Out.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(streetLightsOut),3),
      Sanitation.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(sanitation),3),
      Envir_Complaint.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(EnvirComplaint),3),
      Tree_Trim.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(Treetrim),3),
            Tree_Debris.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), st_c(Treedebris),3),
      )

5. Spatial process of depedent variable

In this part, we focus on the spatial process of the gun crime by calculating a statistic: Local Morans I. The Local Morans I utilizes a spatial weights matrix to relate each grid cell in the fishnet with its neighbors.

## generates warnings from PROJ issues
## {spdep} to make polygon to neighborhoods... 
final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)
## ... and neighborhoods to list of weigths
final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

# print(final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE)
## see ?localmoran
local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$countgunshoot, final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# join local Moran's I results to fishnet
final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(local_morans, as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(Gun_Crime_Count = countgunshoot, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

5.1 Plotting local Morans I results

Then we plot local Morans I results, showing the p-value and significant hot spots for gun crime.

## This is just for plotting
vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans, Variable == i), 
              aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme(title_size = 14) + theme(legend.position="bottom")}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 4, top = "Local Morans I statistics, Gun Crime"))

5.2 Distance to hot spot

The smaller the p-value the more significant the clusters. So the study filters the significant gun crime hot spots using p-value <= 0.001. Here, we use k=1 to calculate the distance from each fishnet center point to its nearest gun crime hot spot as gun.isSig.dist.

# generates warning from NN
final_net <- final_net %>% 
  mutate(gun.isSig = 
           ifelse(local_morans[,5] <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(gun.isSig.dist = 
           nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)),
                       st_c(st_coid(filter(final_net, 
                                           gun.isSig == 1))), 
                       k = 1))

## What does k = 1 represent?

Then we plot NN distance to the gun crime hot spot in the following map:

ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = final_net, aes(fill=gun.isSig.dist), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="NN Distance") +
    geom_sf(data = final_net, color = "grey 50",fill=NA) +
      labs(title="Gun Crime NN Distance") +
      mapTheme()

6. Correlation tests

After studying the spatial process of the dependent variable and risk factors, we then do the correlation test between each risk factor and the gun crime counts to filter the more effective variables for the further modelling.

correlation.long <-
  st_drop_geometry(final_net) %>%
    dplyr::select(-uniqueID, -cvID, -name, -District) %>%
    gather(Variable, Value, -countgunshoot)

correlation.cor <-
  correlation.long %>%
    group_by(Variable) %>%
    summarize(correlation = cor(Value, countgunshoot, use = "complete.obs"))
    
ggplot(correlation.long, aes(Value, countgunshoot)) +
  geom_point(size = 0.1) +
  geom_text(data = correlation.cor, aes(label = paste("r =", round(correlation, 2))),
            x=-Inf, y=Inf, vjust = 1.5, hjust = -.1) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "black") +
  facet_wrap(~Variable, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Gun crime as a function of risk factors") +
  plotTheme()

These correlation scatterplots help us to identify the variables that are more significantly correlated with the dependant variable. But more works and exploration are needed to be done besides pearson correlation test to determine the variables.

7. Cross-validated poisson regression

7.1 Histogram of gun crime

First, we use count histogram to take a look at the distribution of gun crime counts. Given gun crime is a relatively rare event, it makes sense that most grid cells contain no crime events. In this case, an OLS regression is inappropriate. In this section, a Poisson Regression is estimated.

hist(final_net$countgunshoot,main="Gun Crime Histogram",breaks=50,col = c("grey50"))

7.2 Modeling and CV

In this section, we will perform a k-fold variation of the chosen cross-validated poisson regression method, which involves k-fold cross validation and Spatial LOGO-CV.

This regression would be performed four different times. Once using the neighborhood names to distinguish the hold-outs and once using more randomized groups using ID number as the hold-outs.

reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn",  
              "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn","Envir_Complaint.nn","Tree_Debris","Tree_Trim.nn")
reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn",  
                 "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn","gun.isSig","gun.isSig.dist","Envir_Complaint.nn","Tree_Debris","Tree_Trim.nn")

## RUN REGRESSIONS
reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countgunshoot",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countgunshoot, Prediction, geometry)


reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countgunshoot",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countgunshoot, Prediction, geometry)
  
reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countgunshoot",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countgunshoot, Prediction, geometry)


reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",                           
  dependentVariable = "countgunshoot",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = name,countgunshoot,Prediction,geometry)

7.3 Accuracy analysis

reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.cv, Error = Prediction - countgunshoot,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
    
     mutate(reg.ss.cv,        Error = Prediction - countgunshoot,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process"),
    
    mutate(reg.spatialCV,    Error = Prediction - countgunshoot,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors"),                         
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.spatialCV, Error = Prediction - countgunshoot,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Process")) %>%
    st_sf() 

error_by_reg_and_fold <- 
  reg.summary %>%
    group_by(Regression, cvID) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - countgunshoot, na.rm = T),
              MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
              SD_MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup()

Below, error_by_reg_and_fold calculates and visualizes MAE for each fold across each regression. The Spatial Process features seem to reduce errors overall.

LOGO-CV assumes the local spatial process from all other neighborhoods generalizes to the hold-out. When just the risk factors are included in either k-fold or LOGO-CV fold, there are higher errors. However, those large errors disappear when the Spatial Process features are added.

## plot histogram of OOF (out of fold) errors
error_by_reg_and_fold %>%
  ggplot(aes(MAE)) + 
    geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour="black", fill = "#FDE725FF") +
    facet_wrap(~Regression) +
   geom_vline(xintercept = 0) +  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 11, by = 1)) + 
    labs(title="Distribution of MAE", subtitle = "k-fold cross validation vs. Spatial LOGO-CV",
         x="Mean Absolute Error", y="Count") +
    plotTheme()

The table below builds on error_by_reg_and_fold to calculate the mean and standard deviation in errors by regression. The result of the mean and standard deviation in errors shows that the spatial process features improve the model.

st_drop_geometry(error_by_reg_and_fold) %>%
  group_by(Regression) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_MAE = round(mean(MAE), 2),
              SD_MAE = round(sd(MAE), 2)) %>%
  kable() %>%
    kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>%
    row_spec(2, color = "black", background = "#FDE725FF") %>%
    row_spec(4, color = "black", background = "#FDE725FF")
Regression Mean_MAE SD_MAE
Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors 1.37 0.94
Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process 1.11 0.75
Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors 3.51 2.73
Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Process 2.35 1.92

Then we map the LOGO-CV Errors spatially. The maps visualize where the higher errors occur when the local spatial process is not accounted for. It is apparent that the largest errors are in the hotspot location.

error_by_reg_and_fold %>%
  filter(str_detect(Regression, "LOGO")) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = MAE)) +
    facet_wrap(~Regression) +
    scale_fill_viridis() +
    labs(title = "Gun Crime errors by LOGO-CV Regression") +
    mapTheme() + theme(legend.position="bottom")

Based on the following map of risk prediction, we can come to the conclusion that the spatial process features produce a more smooth crime risk surface, relative to the observed counts. These predictions represent latent crime risk - areas at risk even if a crime hasnt actually been observed.

8. Generalizability by neighborhood context

To test wether the algorithm generalize across different neighborhood contexts, we pull race data by Census tract. percentWhite is calculated and tracts are split into two groups: Majority_White and Majority_Non_White.

Then, the table below compares non-absolute errors for the LOGO-CV regressions by raceContext.

tracts20 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B01001_001E","B01001A_001E"), 
          year = 2020, state=17, county=031, geometry=T) %>%
  st_transform('ESRI:102271')  %>% 
  dplyr::select(variable, estimate, GEOID) %>%
  spread(variable, estimate) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B01001_001,
         NumberWhites = B01001A_001) %>%
  mutate(percentWhite = NumberWhites / TotalPop,
         raceContext = ifelse(percentWhite > .5, "Majority_White", "Majority_Non_White")) %>%
  .[neighborhoods,]
reg.summary %>% 
    st_centroid() %>%
    st_join(tracts20) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      group_by(Regression, raceContext) %>%
      summarize(mean.Error = mean(Error, na.rm = T)) %>%
      spread(raceContext, mean.Error) %>%
      kable(caption = "Mean Error by neighborhood racial context") %>%
        kable_styling("striped", full_width = F)

Regression Majority_Non_White Majority_White

Based on the table, our model on average, under-predicts in Majority_Non_White neighborhoods and over-predicts in Majority_White neighborhoods. The Spatial Process model not only reports lower errors overall, but a smaller difference in errors across neighborhood context.

9. Model comparison

9.1 Density vs predictions

Kernal density calculates the density in a particular place using the sum of all the kernels that underlie it. The key scale assumption in kernel density is the use of a global search radius parameter. The following map visualizes three Kernel density maps at three different scales: the radius of 1000, 1500, 2000 feet.

# demo of kernel width
gun_ppp <- as.ppp(st_coordinates(gunshoot), W = st_bbox(final_net))
gun_KD.1000 <- spatstat.core::density.ppp(gun_ppp, 1000)
gun_KD.1500 <- spatstat.core::density.ppp(gun_ppp, 1500)
gun_KD.2000 <- spatstat.core::density.ppp(gun_ppp, 2000)
gun_KD.df <- rbind(
  mutate(data.frame(rasterToPoints(mask(raster(gun_KD.1000), as(neighborhoods, 'Spatial')))), Legend = "1000 Ft."),
  mutate(data.frame(rasterToPoints(mask(raster(gun_KD.1500), as(neighborhoods, 'Spatial')))), Legend = "1500 Ft."),
  mutate(data.frame(rasterToPoints(mask(raster(gun_KD.2000), as(neighborhoods, 'Spatial')))), Legend = "2000 Ft.")) 

gun_KD.df$Legend <- factor(gun_KD.df$Legend, levels = c("1000 Ft.", "1500 Ft.", "2000 Ft."))

ggplot(data=gun_KD.df, aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_raster(aes(fill=layer)) + 
  facet_wrap(~Legend) +
  coord_sf(crs=st_crs(final_net)) + 
  scale_fill_viridis(name="Density") +
  labs(title = "Kernel density with 3 different search radii") +

The comparison shows that the risk prediction model works pretty accurate at the grid cell level to capture observed gun crimes in 2021 compared to the kernel density one. The kernel density predicts the high density of crime even in the area where there is no gun crime obbserved.

However, there are some 2021 observed gun crime points occur in low risk category areas, which means the risk prediction model is still not accurate enough and needs more improvement.

9.3 Bar plot comparison

We calculate the the crime rate for each risk category (1-5th Risk_Category) and model type and create the bar plot to do the comparison. A well fit model should show that the risk predictions capture a greater share of gun crime in the highest risk category relative to the Kernel density.

However, our risk prediction model captures less share of gun crime in high risk categories (4th and 5th risk), which means that the model might need to be improved by doing more feature enigneering.

rbind(gun_KDE_sf, gun_risk_sf) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -label, -Risk_Category) %>%
  group_by(label, Risk_Category) %>%
  summarize(countgunshoot = sum(Value)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(label) %>%
  mutate(Pcnt_of_test_set_crimes = countgunshoot / sum(countgunshoot)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(Risk_Category,Pcnt_of_test_set_crimes)) +
      geom_bar(aes(fill=label), position="dodge", stat="identity") +
      scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, name = "Model") +
      labs(title = "Risk prediction vs. Kernel density, 2021 gun crimes",
           y = "% of Test Set Gun Crime (per model)",
           x = "Risk Category") +
  theme_bw() +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.5))

10. Conclusion

Selection of risk factors based on Broken Windows Theory and the study of spatial process all help to reduce the errors and increase the accuracy of the risk prediction model. Although it performs better than kernel density in capturing the future gun crimes locations, our model is not accurate enough considering the fact that it does not predict some of the future gun crimes in 2021 and it captures less share of gun crime in high risk categories (4th and 5th risk). It means the risk prediction model still need to be improved by further feature enigneering and significant factors selection.

In addition to the low accuracy, another reason that this risk prediction model is not be recommended to be put into production is that the model was created on a foundation of many selection biases. Selection bias is present in the gun crime report database considering that there are more police concentration in the colored neighborhoods and more gun crimes could be reported and recorded in this database. Besides this, the bias also exists in the assumptions we made when identifying risk factors. The risk factors are linked to the Broken Windows Theory and present in physical locations that may be more poor and disordered, in which case, we might miss the more significant risk factors like the gang activities in Chicago. More feature engineering and variable selection work need to be done to increase the algorithms accuracy and reduce the bias.
